data_answer:
The reporter's claim that 400 gallons of coffee would cover half a city block is incorrect because 400 gallons of coffee would instead cover less than half a city block.

 

Half a city block covers 45000 square feet.

This number can be attained by finding the area of the city block and dividing that areaa by two.

 

A = 300 ft * 300 ft = 90000 square feet

Half the city block = A/2 = 45000 square feet

 

Because one gallon equals 13.8 square feet covered, one can calculate that 400 gallons of coffee can cover only about 5520 square feet with simple multiplication.

 

400 gallons * 13.8 square feet/1 gallon = 5520 square feet.

 

Thus, 400 gallons of coffee cover less than half of the city block by about 39480 square feet.

300 square feet x 150 square feet = 45,000 square feet available in half a city block.

THE ANSWER

    It is not correct because the newscaster, Ida Individual, never graduated high school!

    Ida Fallower, as she was named in her youth, was born in 1979 in the small town of Alwayza of  Guinea Pig County, Oklahoma. She, along with her three older brothers, worked on the Fallower family farm in their childhood. They had a heck of a time , always getting through the hard work with the love and support they and their parents had for one another. Everyone in the family surprisingly got along. No one did anything unusual or different. "We were like peas and carrots" Ida once said in an interview for the Nevabea Times. Though the good times didn't last forever...

    Ida enjoyed the farm life, though she found it quite predictable and boring. Occasionally every few months or so they would get deliveries from the factories in Nevebea, the big city in Guinea Pig County, but that was all the excitement she ever felt inside herself in those days.

    When Ida turned sixteen years old, she told her family she had an announcement to make.

    "I love all of you, and I love living with you guys. However, I cannot stay on the farm forever." The Fallower family, which was eating supper at sunset like any ordinary, turned their heads from their meal at once, as if they were controlled with strings by a puppeteer.

    After the shock of change went away from the five, Ida explained how even though the Fallower family had been living on that farm for generations, she just couldn't take the idea of living their forever. She wanted to move to the big city, Nevebea. While she would still miss them, she would be able to visit them on holidays since, afterall, she was still within the boundry lines of Guinea Pig County.  Her parents refused to accept her reasonable ideas and sent her to her room, using the same punishments that all the Fallower's endured when they did something "bad" for generations. The newscaster's claim is incorrect. In fact, the hypothetical spilt 400 gallons of coffee would only cover around 12.3% of half of a city block. An average city block is 300 by 300 feet, or 90000 sq. ft. Therefore, half a city block would be 90000/2 or 45000 sq. ft.

 

Assuming there are 400 gallons of coffee and one gallon of water covers about 13.8 square feet, we can use the equation 400*13.8=g, g being the total area the coffee could cover. Using this equation, we see that g is equal to 5520 square feet -- significantly less than the area of half a city block.

 

The newscaster is wrong.

    The newscaster claims that the coffee from the coffee fountain could cover the equivalent of half a city block which would be 45,000 square feet.

 


    Due to the fact that 400 gallons would only cover 5,520 square feet, the newscaster's claim that it could cover the equivalent of half a city block (45,000 square feet) is incorrect, and, frankly, preposterous.

data_answer: Karissa held her sword tightly against her as her white steed raced forward. Sweat and blood trinkled down her face, but she didn't care. This was it. This was the last one, and if she wouldn't fail. Bryce, on his black steed, raced down the hill right by her side. The army followed behind them shouting and yelling. Karissa marveled at their bravery. They were pretty much running to their deaths, and yet they remained loyal to her and to Bryce, and did not give up or run away. The dark enemy was laid spread out in front of them. Their spears came forward to protect themselves, and she heard one of their captains shout a releasing order. "Arrows!" she called to her The thuds of the arrows came down. She held her shield over her head to protect herself. The enemy now lay only a few yards infront of her. This is it, she said to herself again. She would not fail. She could not fail. She swung her heavy sword, breaking the forming line of the enemy. Her army had the advantage of the horses, which trampled over the bodies of the enemy below. She fought like a madwoman, using all of her strength in every swing. She brought down two or three enemies with each blow. Suddenly, something from behind her grabbed her and pulled her off her horse. She fell to the ground with a thud, but was quickly on her feet again to face an enormous, heavy man. He looked like a bear, in Karissa's opinion. His face was covered with thick black hair, and his skin was incredibly dark. He flashed a white smirk down at her. He held an enormous axe in one hand, and a monstrous sword in the other. "Time to die," he said, then lifted his sword to make a swing. She ducked out of the way, rolling in between his legs and standing up behind him. As he was turning around, she drove her sword into the back of his neck. He screeched, then fell to the ground, dead. On the ground, Karissa found more and more pursuers, but she killed them off easily. She continued to fight for what seemed hours. When the sun was beginning to set, Karissa found herself becoming very weak. Blood trickled down her face, down her arms, everywhere that skin was exposed. Sweat spilled into the cuts, bringing a sharp pain to the wounds Karissa had obtained. A loud shout came from the east. She turned to see, and her heart dropped. It was him. It was the one who started all of this, and who had caused her so much pain, and he was coming right for her. A smile flashed across his face. "Well well well, we meet again." Karissa spat at his feet, glaring up into his evil eyes. "Any last words, Karissa my sweet?" Karissa raised her sword. "My words will be the last words you ever get to hear," she growled. He laughed, then suddenly lunged forward toward her. She blocked his blow with her sword, and shoved him backward, but he pursued again. Over and over he pursued, and she blocked. Her arms were beginning to ache, and he seemed to come at her with full energy and strength. She had been confident before, but now, she didn't know if she could do it. Just as she thought this, he swiped a blow at the back of her legs, knocking her to her knees. He grabbed her arms and knocked the sword out of her hand. He then placed his sword against her neck. "You might as well just admit it, you will always lose." He moved his sword to finish her off. Karissa shut her eyes, but the blow never came. She opened one eye to see a headless man standing infront of her. She cringed backward and jumped to her feet. The headless body fell to the ground. Behind the body was Bryce. He looked down at the body in disgust, bloodied sword raised. He then looked up at Karissa. "Are you alright?" he asked her. She couldn't say anything. She just ran up to him and wrapped grateful arms around him. She didn't know why, but tears began to form in her eyes. "You saved me," she whispered against his neck. "I'll always be here to save you," he whispered in her ear, then placed a kiss on her neck. "Captain!" a voice sounded. Both Karissa and Bryce looked in the direction of the voice. It was one of their leaders. "We have victory!" he shouted. They looked around to see that the enemy had surrendered. They had did so when Bryce cut off the head of their leader. Karissa breathed a sigh of relief. She had did it. She had won.
